text:
South Brunswick, New Jersey is a township of New Jersey.
History.
South Brunswick Township was created by an act of the New Jersey Legislature on February 21, 1798. In the 18th and 19th centuries, the community was mostly agricultural. It was named after the city of Braunschweig (called "Brunswick" in the Low German language), in the state of Lower Saxony, in Germany.
Geography.
According to the United States Census Bureau, in 2010, South Brunswick had a total area of 41.039 square miles (106.290 km2). This included 40.648 square miles (105.278 km2) of land and 0.391 square miles (1.012 km2) of water (0.95%).
Demographics.
At the 2010 United States Census, there were 43,417 people living in South Brunswick.
Transportation.
South Brunswick hosts U.S. Route 1, U.S. Route 130, Route 27, Route 32, and Interstate 95 (the New Jersey Turnpike).
